<HL>
   Letters to the Editor --
   Us in Relation to Them:
   Real Cause for Alarm
</HL>
<DATE>
07/09/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A9
</SO>
<IN>
INTERNATIONAL ECONOMIC NEWS AND STATISTICS (IEN)
ECONOMIC NEWS (ECO)
</IN>
<LP>
   In her haste to bash the Japan-bashers, Susan W. Liebeler
ignores some of the disquieting implications of the Graham
and Krugman study (review of "Foreign Direct Investment in
the United States" by Edward M. Graham and Paul R. Krugman,
Leisure &amp; Arts, June 11). They argue that the competitive
strengths of American firms have declined relative to those
of foreign firms; thus the growth of foreign direct
investment (FDI) is "a part of the general decline of U.S.
economic pre-eminence." While Ms. Liebeler and Messrs. Graham
and Krugman want to draw a sharp line between FDI and the
trade deficits the truth is that a troubling connection does
exist. Both FDI and the trade deficits reflect a declining
ability of American firms to compete with their Japanese and
European rivals.
   If there were no costs to this decline, it would perhaps
be easier to accept the do-nothing policy prescription of
Messrs. Graham and Krugman. But there are real costs. Family
incomes in the U.S. have stagnated since 1973. The wages of
production workers continue to fall by roughly 1% a year. Our
growing international debts have limited American influence
in international affairs.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   My question for Messrs. Graham and Krugman and Ms.
Liebeler is: Why shouldn't we be alarmed at the prospect of
reduced economic and political opportunities?
   Martin Kohli
   Industrial Cooperation Council
   State of New York
   New York
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900709-0096
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900709-0096.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Discovery Airways Loses
   U.S. Operating Authority
</HL>
<DATE>
07/09/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A3
</SO>
<IN>
AIRLINES (AIR)
</IN>
<GV>
TRANSPORTATION DEPARTMENT (TRN)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- The government revoked Discovery Airways'
operating authority, saying the airline failed to take steps
to ensure that it isn't owned or controlled by foreigners.
   The Transportation Department said Discovery failed to
meet several conditions it imposed when it granted the
airline provisional operating authority last spring. Under
U.S. law, foreigners can't control or own more than 25% of
the stock in American airlines.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Hawaiian Airlines, a unit of HAL Inc., had filed suits
charging that Discovery was foreign owned.
   Transportation Secretary Samuel Skinner said that even
after being given "numerous opportunities to satisfy our
concerns over its foreign control and compliance problems . .
. {Discovery} has failed to do so or even to show any
credible inclination to do so."
   The department had required that Philip Ho, owner of 75%
of Discovery's voting stock and president of Japanese-owned
Nansay Hawaii, place his Discovery shares in a voting trust
to prevent Nansay from "exercising control over Discovery
through Mr. Ho." It also ordered the carrier to appoint an
executive committee to direct corporate policy and to
prohibit one of the airline's founders, an Italian citizen,
from serving on it or performing any liaison functions.
   The Transportation Department said Discovery still can
seek a permanent license in a hearing before an
administrative law judge.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900709-0095
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900709-0095.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Hong Kong Legal Officer
   Sentenced for Corruption
</HL>
<DATE>
07/09/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   FREST
</CO>
<LP>
   HONG KONG -- Despite pleas for leniency and promises of
future cooperation with government investigators, the former
chief of the commercial crime unit of Hong Kong's Legal
Department was sentenced to eight years in prison for
corruption.
   Charles Warwick Reid last month pleaded guilty to a charge
of possessing assets deemed disproportionate to his official
income.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   At Friday's sentencing, Hong Kong's chief justice, Sir Ti
Liang Yang, ordered Mr. Reid to pay the local government
HK$12.4 million ($1.6 million), the value of his assets when
he was formally charged in March 1989. Mr. Reid has 28 days
to appeal the court's decision.
   Chief Justice Yang allowed a two-year reduction of the
maximum penalty of 10 years because of Mr. Reid's guilty plea
and his willingness to cooperate with the government.
   Mr. Reid's lawyer, Anthony Corrigan, Queen's Counsel,
argued that the court's leniency would elicit assistance from
the defendant in bringing other corrupt government officials
and businessmen to trial.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900709-0094
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900709-0094.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   DeKalb Genetics to Report Currency Loss,
   Will Slash Fiscal Third-Period Earnings
   ----
   By Scott Kilman
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
07/09/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A4A
</SO>
<CO>
   LATAM SEEDB
</CO>
<IN>
COMMODITY NEWS, FARM PRODUCTS (CMD)
</IN>
<LP>
   DEKALB, Ill -- DeKalb Genetics Corp. expects to report
tomorrow that an unexpectedly large Argentine currency loss
will reduce its net income for the third quarter ended May 31
to less than half of the year-earlier quarter, Bruce P.
Bickner, DeKalb Genetics chairman and chief executive
officer, said.
   That prediction indicates that DeKalb Genetic's fiscal
third-quarter net income will be less than $2.4 million, or
43 cents a share.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   In the 1989 fiscal third quarter, the agricultural seed,
poultry and swine breeding concern generated net income of
$4.8 million, or 85 cents a share, on revenues of $83.8
million. Mr. Bickner said the company expects to report flat
revenues for the most recent third quarter.
   DeKalb Genetics, which sells seed to corn, sorghum and
sunflower farmers in Argentina, was stung by the government's
actions there to curb inflation.
   Before the government's campaign, the company had hedged
some of its receivables in anticipation that the austral, the
Argentine currency, would continue to devalue. But the
government's action resulted in the austral strengthening
against the U.S. dollar. Meanwhile, soaring interest rates
increased the expense of the loan the company had taken to
finance its hedge. As a result, the company expects to report
that its third-quarter interest expense increased
significantly from the year-earlier period.
   The company said it is taking steps to reduce its exposure
to additional currency losses, but that it isn't clear how
long that will take. "The fluctuation in Argentina will
continue to be a problem," said Richard O. Ryan, president of
DeKalb Genetics.
   Because of the drop in third-quarter net income, DeKalb
Genetic's earnings for the year ending Aug. 31 will probably
fall below Wall Street expectations. The fourth quarter
usually isn't a significant period for seed companies such as
DeKalb Genetics, which sell most of their products in the
winter and spring.
   Mr. Bickner said the company expects its net income for
the full year to rise about 15% from the $12.1 million, or
$2.14 a share generated for fiscal 1989.
   That forecast indicates that the company is on the track
to report fiscal 1990 net income of about $2.45 a share. In
the spring, some Wall Street analysts had been expecting the
company to generate fiscal 1990 net income of as much as
$2.90 a share.
   In the U.S., the third quarter ended May 31 is often the
period when seed sales peak. However, this year at DeKalb
Genetics a larger-than-normal proportion of U.S. seed sales
occurred in the second quarter ended Feb. 28, Mr. Bickner
said.
   As a result of this shift, the company's third-quarter
revenues from sales of corn and soybean seeds, among other
things, dropped about 15% from the 1989 third quarter.
   However, total seed sales in the U.S. for the second and
third quarters combined are running ahead of the 1989 pace,
Mr. Bickner said.
   Among other things, U.S. sales of corn seed are expected
to be up 5% from 1989, he said. Mr. Bickner added that the
company's market share of U.S. corn seed probably increased
slightly to more than 9% amid some of the toughest
promotional activity in the industry in several years.
   Price discounting was intense in part because an unusually
wet spring delayed planting for so long that corn farmers had
to trim their plans. As a result, many seed companies expect
to see a higher-than-normal proportion of seed returned to
them by their dealers. Farmers usually won't use seed that
was held over from a planting season until it is retested for
its ability to germinate.
   DeKalb Genetics's weakest-performing seed line this season
has been sorghum. Its supply of sorghum seed was tight
because an October frost reduced the yield of fields it had
planned to have harvested in Texas and Kansas. A few months
later, a freeze damaged its sorghum-seed producing fields in
Florida.
   Mr. Ryan said the company's swine breeding business should
benefit from the trend among farmers to begin expanding their
hog herds. Because of a tight supply of hogs fat enough for
slaughter, the price of hog this spring at times soared about
50% above year earlier levels. Sales of breeding stock in the
third quarter jumped 37% from the same 1989 quarter, he said.
   About 65% of DeKalb Genetic's closely held Class A common
stock, which has voting rights, is controlled by descendants
of the company's founder, Thomas H. Roberts Sr. The company
issues nonvoting Class B common shares to the public.
   In national over-the-counter trading on Friday, DeKalb
Class B shares closed at $43.50, up 50 cents.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900709-0093
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900709-0093.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Bank Results
   In Southwest
   Look Weaker
   ---
   Lower 2nd-Period Net Seen
   Due to Drop in Loans,
   Credit-Quality Problems
   ----
   By Michael Allen
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
07/09/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A4C
</SO>
<CO>
   FBT NCB FCOM SFSI
</CO>
<IN>
BANKS (BNK)
</IN>
<LP>
   Southwestern banks, plagued by continuing credit-quality
problems and sluggish loan demand, generally are expected to
report weaker earnings for the second quarter.
   "A lot of banks are planning to take an unusually heavy
provision for loan losses, trying to build up reserves," said
Bruce Hoyt, an analyst with Boettcher &amp; Co., Denver. "This
will probably be one of the toughest quarters of the year."
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Analysts are even starting to question the health of some
banks that have already been bailed out, such as First City
Bancorp. of Texas and the former Texas banking network of
First RepublicBank Corp., which was bought by NCNB Corp.,
Charlotte, N.C., in 1988. (First RepublicBank isn't related
to First Republic Bancorp of San Francisco.)
   Both rescues included massive infusions of federal aid
that purged the books of sick loans and drastically lowered
the risk to the new owners. But now, concern is rising about
possible problems in the loans extended by the new
managements since they assumed control. Analysts are
particularly worried that the bailed-out banks have been
risking too much of their capital in nationally syndicated
loans financing highly leveraged companies.
   "We think that a story that has been viewed as being
without risk is now taking on a different flavor," writes
Charles W. Peabody, an analyst with Kidder, Peabody &amp; Co., in
a recent report to investors.
   He notes, for example, that loans in NCNB's Texas bank
grew 14% in the year ended March 31, 1990, adjusted for bad
credits that were sloughed off to the Federal Deposit
Insurance Corp. as part of NCNB's takeover agreement. This
increase came despite weak loan demand in Texas. During the
same period, credits extended by banks in the state fell by
13%, according to regulatory statistics.
   Mr. Peabody views this as evidence that a significant
portion of the NCNB-Texas loan growth occurred outside of
Texas in syndicated loans. "We expect additional problems to
surface in the NCNB-Texas bank's portfolio" in the second
quarter, Mr. Peabody writes.
   But Timothy Hartman, vice chairman of NCNB-Texas, denied
Mr. Peabody's assertions. He said that bank's loans actually
grew more than 20% during the period and that "the vast
majority of the loans were to businesses and consumers in
Texas." Mr. Hartman said NCNB-Texas sold more national
credits than it acquired during the period and said
nonperforming loans as a percentage of total loans will be
less than 0.8 of 1% in the second quarter, or below the
percentage at the end of the first quarter. He also said he
expects the Texas unit's earnings to be "comparable" to the
first-quarter figure of over $75 million.
   At First City, a Houston-based bank holding company
acquired in 1988 by an investor group led by A. Robert
Abboud, some problems with out-of-Texas loans have already
bobbed to the surface. Since the beginning of the year, four
major out-of-state borrowers that owe the bank a collective
$72.5 million have filed for bankruptcy-court protection,
including Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. and Federated
Department Stores Inc.
   Mr. Abboud, former chairman of Chicago-based First Chicago
Corp., says he expects to collect the full amount due on the
loans and believes the rise in nonperforming assets is
slowing. But the problems helped contribute to disappointing
earnings during the first quarter. At the end of June, First
City said it expects to report that second-quarter net fell
to between 75 cents and 95 cents a share from $1.08 a year
earlier.
   The weaker earnings also reflect the expense of
consolidating First City's disparate operations. Before the
takeover, First City had 59 separate banks. With the advent
of branch banking in Texas, the new management team has
slimmed that number down to 20, and has consolidated many
back-office functions. Mr. Abboud said he expects to further
reduce staff by about 700 during the next year, or 10%,
through a combination of dismissals and attrition.
   A final reason for First City's poor quarter was a
slowdown in sales from the company's collecting bank, a
separate institution set up to liquidate bad loans that were
on the books before Mr. Abboud's group took over in April
1988. First City, which receives an incentive fee for selling
the assets, said gross collections were around $45 million in
the second quarter, less than half the $104 million collected
in the year-earlier period.
   Mr. Abboud said collections slowed in part because buyers
are waiting to see whether sales by government regulators of
real estate seized along with failed thrifts will drive
prices lower. He said First City held some property off the
market to allow time for demand to rise again. "We will not
discount," he said.
   But some analysts suggest a gloomier explanation: The
collecting bank may have already unloaded most of its
easy-to-sell assets, they say, and further sales might
require deeper price cuts. First City says it doesn't expect
that scenario to happen.
   Elsewhere in the Southwest, several other banks also
reported bad news during the second quarter. First Commerce
Corp., New Orleans, said it expects second-quarter earnings
to fall to between 35 cents and 40 cents a share from 58
cents a share last year.
   First Commerce blamed the decline in part on a rise in
nonperforming assets caused by continued weakness in the New
Orleans and Alexandria, La., markets. The bank holding
company said it doubled its provision for loan losses for the
quarter to $12 million from $6 million in the comparable
period a year ago.
   In Albuquerque, N.M., Sunwest Financial Services Inc. said
it recorded additions to loan-loss reserves and write-downs
totalling $7 million due to a regulatory exam in April. The
bank holding company said in May that it expected "additional
adjustments" due to the exam, as well. The problems "reflect
the continuation of the extremely weak real estate sector and
the slow-growing Albuquerque economy," the company said.
   Meanwhile, Standard &amp; Poor's Corp. recently lowered its
ratings on First Security Corp.'s senior debt to triple-B
from triple-B-plus, citing worries that the Salt Lake City
bank holding company has put creditors at greater risk by
warehousing problem credits at a nonbank subsidiary and using
debt to fund the unit.
   "Although First Security's exposure to commercial real
estate and construction loans has decreased dramatically
since 1985, and little new business has been booked, problems
within the portfolio continue to arise," the rating agency
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
