<HL>
   U.S. and Canada
   To Begin Talks
   On Acid-Rain Pact
   ----
   By Michael McQueen
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
07/09/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B3
</SO>
<CO>
   CANDA
</CO>
<IN>
ENVIRONMENT (ENV)
</IN>
<GV>
EXECUTIVE (EXE)
</GV>
<LP>
   HOUSTON -- Leaders of the U.S. and Canada agreed to begin
negotiations on a treaty to reduce acid-rain emissions.
   The discussions will begin July 16 in Ottawa, said Prime
Minister Brian Mulroney and President Bush in a joint
appearance following a brief meeting. President Bush said he
decided to go ahead with the talks even though Congress has
yet to pass a comprehensive Clean Air Act.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The measure has passed both houses of Congress, and
discussions to resolve differences between the two versions
begin next week. Both versions include specific provisions
for sulfur-dioxide emissions, which produce acid rain. In the
past, the reluctance of the U.S. to enter into such
discussions has been a sticking point in the generally warm
relations between the U.S. and Canada.
   The treaty could include specific timetables for reducing
acid-rain emissions, details for a joint research and
monitoring program and provisions for settling disputes.
   Although the two leaders, meeting before the start of the
economic summit of industrial nations, emphasized the
progress in resolving environmental issues, their talks came
amid lingering disagreement among the summit partners over
environmental issues.
   A draft copy of the environmental portion of the summit
communique obtained by this newspaper shows that more than
one-third of the document remains in dispute, with pre-summit
negotiators unable to decide on such issues as whether global
climate change is the most important environmental issue
facing humanity, or only one of several environmental
priorities.
   Summit leaders are also expected to discuss the importance
of preserving forest land and helping underdeveloped nations
protect their environments while promoting economic
development. But they disagree on how extensive this
assistance should be.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900709-0064
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900709-0064.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   ABF Mulls an Offer
   To Berisford for Some
   Of Its Food Concerns
   ----
   Special to The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
07/09/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B7A
</SO>
<CO>
   U.BRF U.ABF
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
FOOD PRODUCTS (FOD)
</IN>
<LP>
   LONDON -- Associated British Foods PLC, or ABF, said it's
considering making an offer for British Sugar and other
food-manufacturing companies of Berisford International PLC,
the troubled United Kingdom food, financial-services,
property, commodities and industrial group.
   Berisford previously had said it was willing to sell any
part of its business to reduce its net debt of #1.02 billion
($1.82 billion). At the same time, the company reported a
sharp deterioration in net earnings attributable to
shareholders as a result of provisions taken against New York
property investments.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   ABF, which owns 23% of Berisford, said the only solution
open to Berisford is the early sale of its profitable British
Sugar unit. Analysts have estimated the sale of the sugar
operations could fetch as much as #1 billion.
   A spokesman for Berisford said the two companies had been
involved in talks for two weeks with a view to ABF making an
offer for all of Berisford. "There are several people who
have been discussing various things with Berisford," he said.
   He added that some of those involved in talks were foreign
companies.
   Harry Bailey, ABF's chief executive officer, said ABF
wants to "sit down and discuss" making an offer for British
Sugar that could also include Berisford's flavors,
fragrances, and fruits and nuts importing units as well as
businesses that are associated with British Sugar, like its
beat pulp unit.
   ABF said an early sale of British Sugar would allow
Berisford to realize optimum value for its remaining assets
and reduce the need for forced sales.
   Mr. Bailey said ABF had #1 billion in cash available for a
purchase, although he said that figure couldn't be used as an
indication of what ABF considered British Sugar to be worth.
   British Sugar is the main component of Berisford's Bristar
food and agribusiness division. In the six months ended March
31, British Sugar's profit before interest and taxes rose 19%
to #59.1 million from #49.6 million the year before.
Berisford's overall profit before interest dropped 21% to
#57.2 million from #72.6 million.
   In its latest results, ABF said pretax profit for the year
to March 31 jumped 20% to #284 million from #237 million and
earnings per share rose 18% to 14.67 pence from 12.4 pence.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
