<HL>
   What's News --
   Business and Finance
</HL>
<DATE>
07/09/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1
</SO>
<LP>
   UAL'S UNIONS said five major banks agreed to lead the
labor group's effort to get financing for a proposed $4.38
billion acquisition of United Airlines. The buy-out group,
which faces an Aug. 9 deadline, said the banks insist that
part of the financing come from non-banking sources, such as
aircraft suppliers.
   ---
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The jobless rate fell to 5.2% in June although only 40,000
new jobs were created during the month. Many economists
believe unemployment can't go any lower without rekindling
inflation. The June figures aren't likely to prompt the Fed
to ease credit.
                                                                                                       

   Stock prices gained despite a rise in interest rates
following the employment report. The Dow industrials advanced
25.74 points to 2904.95.
   ---
   RJR Nabisco has been deluged with $7 billion of loan
commitments from banks for its debt refinancing plan, more
than triple what it needs. The influx suggests that big money
is once again becoming available for leveraged-company
transactions.
   ---
   The S&amp;L fraud investigation will concentrate initially on
100 thrifts, following Democratic charges that the
administration wasn't pursuing the investigation vigorously
enough.
   ---
   British Airways ordered 21 Boeing 747-400 jets valued at
$3.8 billion and took options on 12 others, which could bring
the deal's value to $6.4 billion.
   ---
   Renault plans to begin a $99 million tender offer this
week for the 55% of Mack Trucks it doesn't already own.
   ---
   A tax increase passed by the Massachusetts Legislature
will put a 5% levy on fees charged by lawyers, accountants,
engineers and architects. Business leaders said it would
further cripple the state's sluggish economy.
   ---
   E.M. Warburg isn't considering selling any of the
Ingersoll newspapers it acquired last week, although it may
face drawn-out negotiations over debt payments to
bondholders.
   ---
   Lead and zinc prices are expected to jump as union workers
at Cominco Ltd., Canada's biggest producer of the metals,
prepared to strike today.
   ---
   Shearson was fined a record $500,000 by the Big Board for
its trading in E.F. Hutton stock when it was discussing
taking over Hutton in 1986.
   ---
   A chemical plant explosion in Texas that left 17 dead is
being investigated to determine whether contract workers were
a factor. The Arco plant had 430 full-time employees, 80 of
them lower-paid contract workers.
   ---
   Digital Equipment is expected to unveil today a new
generation of its strong-selling MicroVAX computer line,
marking a fresh challenge to IBM in the minicomputer market.
   ---
   Lord Geller will merge into another WPP Group ad agency,
marking the end of the once-hot shop that never fully
recovered from the defection of six top executives in 1988.
   ---
   Markets --
   Stocks: Volume 111,730,000 shares. Dow Jones industrials
2904.95, up 25.74; transportation 1140.69, up 9.67; utilities
206.11, off 0.06.
   Bonds: Shearson Lehman Hutton Treasury index 3423.07, off
33.34.
   Commodities: Dow Jones futures index 132.97, off 0.91;
spot index 133.45, off 0.92.
   Dollar: 151.70 yen, up 1.10; 1.6520 marks, up 0.0003.
</TEXT>
