<HL>
   Economic Summit (A Special Report): Getting Ready
   ---
   For Houston, a Chance to Prove It's Hot
   ----
   By Caleb Solomon
</HL>
<DATE>
07/09/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE R20
</SO>
<LP>
   HOUSTON -- This city has been preparing, too -- but not
just for a cadre of world leaders and their erudite aides.
   Still smarting from the collapse of its oil and
real-estate industries in the mid-1980s, America's
fourth-largest city is determined to prove it is alive and
well. So, in the belief that as many as 4,000 media
representatives will flock to this week's summit, Houston has
prepared a public-relations extravaganza.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Months ago, a host committee of 270 top civic, business
and cultural leaders marshaled time, services and products
donated by 10,000 volunteers and prepared to scrub the city's
image. An extraordinary 10-week cleanup drive removed two
million pounds of trash from targeted streets and
neighborhoods. Trees were planted, and special red-and-white
flowers were added along some routes leading to the summit
site, Rice University. (Those colors look best on TV, experts
decided.)
   A "Media Fest" party has been organized, and the night
before sessions begin, favorite son President Bush will play
host to summit luminaries -- and, of course, the press -- at
a barbecue and rodeo.
   The Houston Friendly Committee even devised a special
summit slogan "as a way of encouraging Houstonians to be
friendly to . . . the news media and other dignitaries." The
phrase? "Houston's Hot."
   Which it is. World leaders and reporters willing to
venture outdoors may encounter daytime temperatures well
above 90 degrees and morning humidity around 90%. But civic
boosters insist that's dandy, providing the opening for
well-coached citizens to assure reporters and other visitors
they encounter that Houston is also "hot" when it comes to
its business climate, port facility, energy industry, and
aerospace, medical and convention facilities. (Houstonians
got a pre-summit version of the campaign.)
   "We will convert that negative {the climate} to not only a
positive but to a focused sales opportunity," promised oil
man George Strake, co-chairman of the host committee, who
announced the slogan on a June day when temperature had
already hit 95 degrees.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900709-0013
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900709-0013.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Economic Summit (A Special Report): On the Agenda
   ---
   The G7: Past Its Prime?
   ----
   By Peter Truell
</HL>
<DATE>
07/09/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE R9
</SO>
<CO>
   EUROP JAPAN CANDA FORGN
</CO>
<IN>
INTERNATIONAL ECONOMIC NEWS AND STATISTICS (IEN)
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
FOREIGN-EXCHANGE MARKETS (FRX)
</IN>
<GV>
TREASURY DEPARTMENT (TRE)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- Is it possible to suffer from hardening of
the arteries at the age of five? Not likely, maybe, but that
is precisely what some financiers think is happening to the
Group of Seven.
   The G-7, as it's commonly known, is not to be confused
with the the summit group meeting this week, which is led by
heads of state and which frequently is called the Seven. The
G-7, by contrast, has 15 members -- the finance ministers and
central-bank chieftains of those same seven countries, plus
the head of the International Monetary Fund.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Formally established in 1986, the G-7 is the world's most
exclusive and powerful economic club. It will play an
important part in translating into action some of the
initiatives that the heads of state decide upon at this
summit, but its writ runs well beyond that into regulation of
a huge hunk of the global economy, and its pronouncements
frequently move world markets.
   In its first years of life, G-7 used its clout effectively
in dealing with major economic problems. It did much to
stabilize an unruly U.S. dollar, it coordinated interest-rate
moves on an unprecedented global scale, and it intervened
speedily to help ensure that the world-wide stock-market dive
in 1987 didn't drag the planet into recession.
   But it hasn't done an awful lot lately, and people are
beginning to wonder whether the club members aren't napping
in their wing chairs, victims of early senescence. G-7's
statements, critics point out, have grown more and more
predictable, constantly calling for lower inflation and
higher savings without spelling out concrete steps to achieve
either. Over the past couple of years, its meetings have
produced no major initiatives beyond some relatively modest
fiddling with the industrialized nations' strategy for
handling Third World debt.
   "Has the G-7 become irrelevant?" asks Thomas Berger, a
former U.S. Treasury Department official and now director of
a unit of Swiss bank Lombard Odier &amp; Cie. Increasingly, yes,
he and others believe. In a recent essay, he concluded that
"the essential elements of the current G-7 strategy were
formulated in 1985. Like an automobile of this vintage, it is
time for an overhaul."
   Balderdash, say the club members. If something isn't
broken, they ask, why fix it? If G-7 is quiet now, they
maintain, that's because its policies have worked so well.
   Treasury Secretary Nicholas Brady says the U.S. and its
partners have been "successful in maintaining growth,
reducing trade and current account imbalances, containing
inflation and promoting exchange-rate stability." He contends
that G-7 strengthened and lengthened the economic expansion,
now into its eighth consecutive year, and increased its
resiliency in the face of periodic financial market
instability.
   There is a great deal of truth in this, and even the
critics do not contest it. But there is also a growing
feeling the G-7 is not being vigorous enough now in managing
currency-exchange rates and other undramatic financial chores
-- work that, if left undone, could lead to bigger problems
later. "The wolf isn't at the door," says Robert Solomon of
Brookings Institution, a Washington think tank. "It's just
that we've got termites in the woodwork."
   The G-7 may not agree, but it knows that in the world of
international finance perception can be as important as fact.
So, at its next meeting -- a fall conclave is probable -- a
new item is likely to be on the agenda: a discussion of
charges that the group has been resting on its laurels. For
now, the critics can only hope that the response will mean
closer management of the world economy by the members of the
club.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900709-0012
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900709-0012.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Safety Training
   Under Scrutiny
   In Arco Blast
   ----
   By Caleb Solomon
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
07/09/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A2
</SO>
<CO>
   RCM ARC LABOR
</CO>
<IN>
CHEMICALS, PLASTICS (CHM)
</IN>
<GV>
LABOR DEPARTMENT (LBR)
</GV>
<LP>
   CHANNELVIEW, Texas -- Investigators of a fiery Arco
Chemical Co. plant explosion that killed 17 workers here late
last week are trying to determine whether contract workers
were a factor, but the cause of the blast isn't yet known.
   The explosion is the latest in a recent rash of
petrochemical and oil refinery blasts that has prompted
closer scrutiny of plant operations by government, industry
and union officials and tougher enforcement of safety rules.
A Phillips Petroleum Co. explosion killed 23 workers in
October at a chemical plant about a dozen miles from here.
Hundreds of other workers have been injured or killed in the
past two years as such accidents seem to be on the rise
around the country.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   "We are concerned about what is happening in the
petrochemical industry," said Gerard Scannell, head of the
Occupational Safety and Health Administration, in an
interview. Mr. Scannell and OSHA investigators were on the
scene at Channelview within hours of the explosion.
   Industry officials are searching for answers and many have
reviewed their safety practices. "We can't explain this
bunching {of accidents}," said Lodwrick Cook, chairman of
both the chemical company and Atlantic Richfield Co., the oil
giant that owns 83% of the chemical company. "It's
troubling."
   "This situation is accelerating," said Joseph Misbrener,
president of the Oil, Chemical and Atomic Workers union in
Denver. "It is definitely a crisis." The union has been
distributing a videotape narrated by Ralph Nader called "Out
of Control" on the industry's problems.
   The Arco blast occurred at a waste-water treatment tank
where maintenance workers were about to fix a compressor,
said Arco officials, who wouldn't speculate on the cause of
the accident until the company and federal authorities
complete their separate investigations.
   The eruption and ensuing blaze that began around 11:30
Thursday night destroyed an area about the size of a city
block at the plant. Tremors from the blast were felt for
miles. It took firefighters four hours to put out the fire at
the facility here, about 20 miles east of Houston.
   OSHA and industry critics have been focusing on the
increased reliance of contract workers in chemical plants and
refineries who, they say, often don't get the same training
as company workers. Mr. Scannell said OSHA commissioned a
study, due by the end of summer, to see if there's a
correlation between the use of contract workers and safety
problems.
   Of the 17 who died here, five were Arco employees, 11 were
contract employees working for Austin Industrial Inc. and one
was a truck driver, Arco said. The plant employs about 350
Arco workers and 80 contract workers full time.
   Arco officials said the contract workers they use receive
the same training as Arco employees. "We treat the contract
employees, who are routinely part of our work force and part
of our plant, as we do our own employees," said Jack Johnson,
senior vice president. Austin Industrial officials couldn't
be reached for comment.
   Union officials maintain that companies use contract
workers because they receive lower wages and benefits than
full-time company employees. While acknowledging that
contract workers are less expensive, Arco officials insisted
the plant uses them to maintain flexibility, not to cut
costs.
   Past accident investigations have also focused on a lack
of preventive maintenance, excessive overtime, inadequate
safety practices and the running of equipment at or above
capacity.
   OSHA has stepped up penalties against companies it
believes made willful and flagrant violations. The agency
levied a $5.7 million fine against Phillips, which the
company is contesting. In the past, OSHA penalties involving
worker deaths often totaled in the hundreds of dollars.
   Arco officials said it could take several months for the
entire plant to restart but that some portions could be
brought on line much sooner. The plant makes a much-in-demand
gasoline additive, methyl tertiary butyl ether, which has
received a big environmental push because it reduces gasoline
evaporation. Arco officials said production could resume
within a few weeks, which analysts said shouldn't affect the
market.
   The plant also makes propylene oxide, used to make foam in
seat cushions and mattresses, and styrene monomer, used as a
food-packaging material. An extended shutdown could boost
prices of these chemicals, analysts said.
   ---
   Alex London contributed to this article.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
