<HL>
   Shearson Lehman
   Is Fined $500,000
   By the Big Board
   ----
   By William Power
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
07/09/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C10
</SO>
<CO>
   SLH AXP
</CO>
<IN>
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
SECURITIES INDUSTRY (SCR)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- The New York Stock Exchange censured American
Express Co.'s Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. unit and fined it a
record $500,000 for Shearson's trading of E.F. Hutton &amp; Co.
stock during 1986 takeover talks.
   Shearson, without admitting or denying the allegations,
consented to the exchange's findings that it violated Big
Board rules in its purchases and sales of Hutton stock
between August and October 1986, while Shearson was making an
unsuccessful effort to acquire Hutton. About a year after
that aborted effort to acquire Hutton, Shearson succeeded in
buying the firm for nearly $1 billion.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   A separate Securities and Exchange Commission
investigation of the matter has been dropped, people familiar
with the case said. The SEC declined to comment.
   The Big Board's investigation involved Shearson's purchase
of Hutton stock before the two firms began exploratory talks
on a merger in late September and October 1986. By Sept. 19,
according to the Big Board, Shearson had bought about 1.5
million shares, or 4.9%, of Hutton's common, just under the
5% level that requires public disclosure.
   Shearson sold about a third of its Hutton holdings Oct.
15; the next day, Hutton announced the talks were off, and
its stock price plunged.
   The Big Board found that Shearson had engaged in "conduct
inconsistent with just and equitable principles of trade" in
connection with the Hutton stock sale. Separately, the Big
Board said Shearson had broken rules in its acquisition of
the Hutton stake by failing to mark certain Hutton purchases
as trades for the firm's own account, rather than for
customers.
   Besides the record fine, the Big Board ordered Shearson to
appoint a lawyer who for at least three years will advise it
on rules involving securities transactions for its own
account.
   Shearson, in a statement, said: "We did not violate any
law or existing interpretation of the exchange rules. We
determined to settle rather than going through a protracted
process over actions that took place years ago."
   As for the alleged violations involving the marking of
trades for its own account, Shearson said: "We took steps
before there was any indication of a disciplinary proceeding
to help prevent similar processing errors from occurring
again."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900709-0004
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900709-0004.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Economy -- Tracking the Economy:
   Inflation Is in the Spotlight as Reports
   On Prices, Credit, Retail Sales Are Due
   ----
   By Pamela Sebastian
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
07/09/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A2
</SO>
<IN>
ECONOMIC NEWS (ECO)
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Trickle-down from June's so-so jobs report
should damp industrial-output data and focus attention on the
next economic bugaboo: inflation.
   Economists surveyed after Friday's employment-report
release said they expect June industrial production, due out
next week,to fall far short of May's 0.6% gain. Meanwhile,
attention turns toward the June producer price index, which
is expected to show a slight increase. The PPI is due out
Friday along with June retail sales. This week's other major
indicator is May's consumer credit, due out today.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Much attention lately has focused on whether the Federal
Reserve will ease credit, giving the flagging 7 1/2-year-old
economic expansion a shot in the arm. Economists generally
viewed the June jobs data as inconclusive: soft, but not weak
enough to prod the Fed to lower interest rates.
   Lawrence Kudlow, chief economist at Bear, Stearns &amp; Co.,
New York, said the next checkpoint for possible Fed action
may come with the June inflation figures.
   "That's where the rubber could meet the road," he said.
Mr. Kudlow expects only a 0.1% increase in the June PPI after
May's 0.3% advance. And he envisions another tame inflation
reading from next week's June consumer price index. He holds
that lower inflation, against the backdrop of a slower
economy, could encourage the Fed to ease credit and help
stimulate the economy. "I think this economy is really on the
cusp of recession," he said.
   Of course, not everyone agrees with Mr. Kudlow about
recession. David Resler, chief economist at Nomura Securities
International Inc., New York, said that the "best read on the
{jobs} number" is simply that it confirms "that the economy
isn't growing very much." The slowdown in manufacturing jobs
has been discernible for some time, he said. And the recent
slackening of job growth in the important services area
"doesn't seem to be causing widespread weakness in the
service sector as yet -- with the emphasis on yet," noted Mr.
Resler.
   He expects industrial production to show a rise of 0.4%
for June, with half the gain coming from stronger mining and
utility production. The consensus view calls for only a 0.2%
increase in June output, according to MMS International, a
unit of McGraw-Hill Inc., New York. In May, industrial
production rose 0.6%. Capacity utilization is expected to
remain unchanged at 83.6%, according to the MMS survey.
   The consensus view on the June PPI calls for a rise of
0.2%, down slightly from May's 0.3% advance. Consumer prices
are expected to show a rise of 0.3% for June, up slightly
from May's 0.2% increase.
   Economists said producer prices should benefit from
another drop in energy prices, helping to offset upward
pressure from capital-goods prices. Higher tobacco prices are
expected to tug upward on the index.
   Donald Fine, economist at Chase Manhattan Bank, New York,
believes "the threat of a recession right now is fairly
small," although he noted there aren't any great signs of
vigor, either. "The economy is sort of bopping along at a
1.5% growth rate and that, in the long run, will help
moderate inflation," Mr. Fine said. He expects both the June
PPI and CPI to increase 0.3%.
   A rebound in auto sales in June is thought to have helped
retail sales move into the plus column after two months of
fairly steep declines. The consensus view calls for a 0.6%
gain in retail sales, according to MMS. Excluding auto sales,
that gain narrows to 0.3%, it said.
   In May, sluggish auto sales, along with subdued
general-merchandise buying, are thought to have contributed
to another sluggish consumer-credit report. In April,
consumer credit expanded $600 million.
   ---
