<HL>
   What's News --
   World-Wide
</HL>
<DATE>
07/09/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1
</SO>
<LP>
   BUSH IS FOCUSING on agricultural issues at the economic
summit in Houston.
   The president will urge leaders of the major Western
nations -- especially the European Community -- to commit
themselves to certain changes in agriculture in order to
guarantee success in the current round of global
trade-liberalization talks, U.S. officials said. Bush's
comments will ensure a contentious opening day at the
three-day summit. The U.S., a major agricultural exporter,
favors sharp cuts and the eventual elimination of farm
subsidies, while the EC has argued that it can't do away with
the subsidies without damaging its social fabric.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The group isn't likely to agree on economic aid for the
Soviets. The U.S. believes the aid would be wasted without
certain preconditions -- such as a commitment to free-market
principles.
   ---
   GORBACHEV TOLD farmers and workers to back him or find a
new leader.
   The Soviet president, addressing a gathering of workers on
the eve of nominations for Communist Party leader, asked the
group, "Am I needed by you? You will decide." Delegates at a
party congress will vote on the nominations later this week,
and both hard-liners and moderates say Gorbachev appears
certain to weather the sharp criticism of his policies and be
re-elected general-secretary of the party. But the rest of
the ruling Politburo, which the congress also will elect,
could be completely overhauled, with a new generation of
conservatives rising to power.
   A Soviet spokesman said Moscow's assistance to Cuba will
"fade away, but not tomorrow." The U.S. has said aid to the
Kremlin depends on such a move.
   ---
   Louisiana's Legislature passed a bill that would send
doctors to prison for up to 10 years for doing abortions. The
bill, which also sets a $100,000 fine, would allow abortions,
however, in cases of rape or incest. The Senate earlier
yesterday had failed to override Gov. Roemer's veto of a
similar bill that didn't include the exceptions.
   ---
   The U.S. and Canada agreed to begin negotiations on a
treaty to cut acid-rain emissions. Canadian leader Mulroney
and President Bush, both in Houston for the economic summit,
said the talks would start next week. Bush said he decided to
proceed with talks even though Congress has yet to pass a
Clean Air Act.
   ---
   The U.N. secretary-general sent an envoy to Albania to try
to help solve the crisis in Tirana, the capital, where up to
6,000 dissidents have taken refuge in foreign embassies.
Perez de Cuellar, who is acting as an intermediary, said he
was hopeful some people would be allowed to leave Albania but
that "most should stay in their country."
   ---
   Bulgarian student leaders demanded that more of the
country's ruling Socialist Party leaders step down after
public protests forced President Mladenov to resign. The
53-year-old leader, who ousted Communist hard-liner Zhivkov
in November, quit Friday because of charges that he requested
tanks to crush a December demonstration.
   ---
   Greek and U.S. officials signed a defense treaty allowing
two major U.S. military bases to remain in Greece for at
least eight years. Washington sweetened the pact by providing
Athens with 62 warplanes and four naval destroyers. The U.S.
agreed to sharply reduce American military personnel in
Greece and to close two other bases.
   ---
   Bush will permit U.S. commercial satellites to be launched
by Soviet rockets, according to Baker. But the secretary of
state said he didn't know when the first American satellite
would be carried by a Soviet rocket. Plans call for the
rocket to be launched from a base in northern Australia.
   ---
   More than 22,000 youths die each year from injuries, with
homicides and suicides accounting for one-fifth of the
fatalities, according to a report produced for Congress by
the Centers for Disease Control. The study calls for schools,
local governments and families to put an increased emphasis
on injury prevention.
   ---
   Nine white extremists were detained in connection with a
series of recent bombings aimed at anti-apartheid targets,
South Africa's minister of law and order said. He stated that
they hadn't yet been charged.
   ---
   Two Kenyan lawyers were given refuge in the U.S. Embassy
in Nairobi, according to a newspaper owned by the ruling
party. The lawyers were described as leading opponents of the
country's one-party rule.
   ---
   Stefan Edberg of Sweden won the Wimbledon men's singles
tennis title for the second time, defeating defending champ
Boris Becker of West Germany, three sets to two. On Saturday,
Martina Navratilova of the U.S. captured a record ninth
women's Wimbledon title by winning her match against American
Zina Garrison in straight sets.
   ---
   West Germany won the World Cup soccer title for the third
time by beating Argentina, 1-0, in Rome. The West Germans had
lost to the Argentines in the 1986 final in Mexico.
   ---
   Died: Bill Cullen, 70, television personality and game
show host whose broadcast career spanned more than 40 years,
Saturday, in Los Angeles, of lung cancer.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900709-0080
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900709-0080.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Autos:
   Japan Cars
   Score Sales
   Coup in U.S.
   ----
   By Neal Templin
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
07/06/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B1
</SO>
<CO>
   GM F C HMC TOYOY NSANY J.MZD J.MOT SBRU J.IZM C.HYU G.VOW
VOLVY J.SUZ G.BMW S.SAA G.AUD J.DHM F.PEU I.ALR G.POR
</CO>
<IN>
AUTOMOBILES (AUT)
</IN>
<LP>
   DETROIT -- Japanese auto makers grabbed a record share of
U.S. car sales in the first half, which ended with a late
June sales surge.
   Sales of North American-made cars and trucks in late June
rose 11.9% to the most robust sales pace in six months,
bringing some relief to a struggling industry.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   But the big winners for the first half of the year were
the Japanese, who took 28% of total car sales -- domestic and
imported -- compared with just 24% in the year-earlier
period. Detroit's share dropped to 65% from 69%.
   Never before has Japanese market share been so high for a
six-month period, says John Casesa, auto analyst with
Wertheim Schroeder &amp; Co. in New York. "Japanese market share
will continue to increase," he predicts.
   Among the first half's highlights:
   -- Toyota Motor Corp., Honda Motor Co. and Mitsubishi
Motors Corp. were the big winners. Their car sales surged
31.5%, 13.5% and 88%, respectively, thanks to big increases
in production from their U.S. factories.
   -- The Japanese had some losers as well, however. Nissan
Motor Co.'s first-half car sales dropped 13.6%, and Subaru of
America Inc.'s sales plunged 31.1%. Neither company has
strong products in the major segments of the market.
   -- General Motors Corp., a big loser in recent years, held
its own in the first half, with a 35.7% car-market share,
about equal with a year earlier. But Ford Motor Co.'s market
share dipped nearly two percentage points, to 20.8%, while
Chrysler Corp.'s share nose-dived to 8.9% from 10.6% a year
earlier.
   Detroit's Big Three did better in the light truck market
because of their strength in pickups, minivans and Jeep-like
vehicles. Japanese auto makers are just beginning to make
serious stabs at this growing part of the overall vehicle
market.
   Domestically produced cars hit a seasonally adjusted
annual selling rate of 8.1 million vehicles in late June, far
higher than forecast and the strongest selling pace since
early January. It compares with a 7.1 million rate a year ago
and a 6.8 million rate in mid-June of this year.
   "I feel there's some momentum with us now," says Fred
Ricart, a Columbus, Ohio, Ford dealer, who had strong sales
in late June. If so, that bodes well for the U.S. economy,
because it would portend a pickup in consumer spending.
Analysts and auto makers caution, however, that one 10-day
sales period alone isn't enough to warrant strong
conclusions.
   But throughout the first half, Japanese auto makers as a
group turned in a strong performance. Their unprecedented
market share stems directly from their rapidly growing U.S.
manufacturing operations. Ironically, only a few years ago,
Big Three executives were calling for the Japanese to build
factories in the U.S. to create a "level playing field" of
competition.
   Some Japanese companies, notably Toyota and Mitsubishi,
are aggressively pursuing fleet sales, once the exclusive
domain of Detroit's Big Three. And while Detroit's quality
has improved greatly in recent years, the Japanese still
lead, especially in the minds of many consumers. "The
perception that the Japanese cars are better is still out
there," said analyst David Healey of Barclays de Zoette Wedd
in New York City.
   Honda Motor Co. sold 86,872 cars for all of June, a 58.2%
increase from a year earlier. A company spokesman said
year-ago sales were pulled down in the wake of a dealer
incentive program that ended in May 1989.
   GM posted an especially strong 18.2% gain in total vehicle
sales for the last 10 days of June. The No. 1 car maker's
Chevrolet and Pontiac divisions each had big increases. "As
we begin the final months of the 1990 model year and enter
into the second half of the calendar year, we are optimistic
that General Motors will continue to improve its market
share," said James B. Fitzpatrick, GM's vice president of
marketing and product planning.
   Ford, meanwhile, saw its overall sales rise 2% in late
June from a year ago, well below the rest of the market.
Ford's domestic truck sales rose 14.1%, but its domestic car
sales dropped 4.7%.
   Chrysler's total vehicle sales fell 12.6% in late June,
continuing a pattern of badly lagging its competitors that
has continued since February. Chrysler has some big holes in
its car lineup, and its new line of luxury cars haven't
caught on with consumers.
   ---
